{
  "What should you always wear to protect your eyes during a lab experiment?": "",
  "Sunglasses": "",
  "Safety goggles": "",
  "Reading glasses": "",
  "A face shield only": "",
  "Safety goggles are specifically designed to protect eyes from chemical splashes, flying debris, and other hazards. Regular glasses and sunglasses do not provide adequate protection because they have gaps around the edges.": "",
  "What is the first thing you should do if a chemical splashes in your eyes?": "",
  "Rub your eyes to remove the chemical quickly": "",
  "Continue working and wash eyes after the lab": "",
  "Flush your eyes with water at the eyewash station for at least 15 minutes": "",
  "Apply a bandage over the affected eye immediately": "",
  "If a chemical splashes in your eyes, immediately go to the eyewash station and flush both eyes with water for at least 15 minutes. Rubbing your eyes can cause more damage by spreading the chemical.": "",
  "Why should you never eat or drink in the laboratory?": "",
  "Food and drinks might spill on your lab notebook and ruin the data": "",
  "Chemicals could accidentally contaminate food and be swallowed": "",
  "Eating slows down your ability to conduct the experiment on time": "",
  "The teacher needs to see everyone working at their stations only": "",
  "Chemical residue on hands, counters, or in the air could transfer to food or drinks. Consuming contaminated food could cause poisoning or illness. This is why eating and drinking are never allowed in labs.": "",
  "What should you do with long hair during a lab experiment?": "",
  "Leave it down so it stays out of your face naturally": "",
  "Tie it back to prevent it from catching fire or getting caught in equipment": "",
  "Cut it short before every lab period for maximum safety": "",
  "Cover it with aluminum foil to protect it from chemical vapors": "",
  "Long hair should always be tied back during lab work. Loose hair can catch fire from Bunsen burners, dip into chemicals, or get tangled in equipment, creating serious safety hazards.": "",
  "Where is the fire extinguisher typically located in a science lab?": "",
  "In a locked cabinet that only the teacher can access": "",
  "Near the exit door in a clearly visible and accessible location": "",
  "Under each student's lab bench for immediate personal use": "",
  "In the teacher's office next door to the lab room itself": "",
  "Fire extinguishers are mounted in visible, easily accessible locations near exits. Students should know where safety equipment is located before starting any lab activity.": "",
  "What should you do if you accidentally break a glass beaker?": "",
  "Pick up the pieces with your bare hands and throw them in the trash": "",
  "Leave it on the floor and hope nobody steps on the broken glass": "",
  "Tell the teacher immediately and use a brush and dustpan to clean up": "",
  "Hide the broken pieces under the table so nobody notices them": "",
  "Notify your teacher immediately. Broken glass should be swept up with a brush and dustpan — never picked up with bare hands. Dispose of it in a designated broken glass container, not a regular trash can.": "",
  "Why should you never smell chemicals directly by putting your nose over the container?": "",
  "Because chemical fumes could irritate or damage your respiratory system": "",
  "Because the smell will linger on your clothes for the entire day": "",
  "Because it might cause the chemical to evaporate faster than expected": "",
  "Because your nose will block the opening and prevent proper mixing": "",
  "Chemical fumes can be toxic, corrosive, or irritating. Instead of sniffing directly, use the wafting technique — gently wave your hand over the container to direct a small amount of vapor toward your nose.": "",
  "What type of footwear should you wear during a lab?": "",
  "Open-toed sandals for comfort during long experiments": "",
  "Closed-toe shoes that cover the entire foot for safety": "",
  "Flip-flops because they are easy to remove if chemicals spill": "",
  "No shoes at all to avoid tracking chemicals out of the lab": "",
  "Closed-toe shoes protect your feet from dropped equipment, broken glass, and chemical spills. Open-toed shoes expose your feet to these hazards and are not allowed in labs.": "",
  "What should you always do before starting a lab activity?": "",
  "Read and understand all instructions and safety precautions for the lab": "",
  "Begin mixing chemicals immediately to save as much time as possible": "",
  "Rearrange the lab equipment into a pattern you find more convenient": "",
  "Share your goggles with a partner to reduce the amount of waste": "",
  "Always read the entire lab procedure and safety precautions before beginning. Understanding what you will do helps prevent accidents and ensures you know how to handle any hazards involved.": "",
  "What is the correct way to smell a chemical in the lab?": "",
  "Put your nose directly over the container opening and inhale deeply": "",
  "Use your hand to gently waft the fumes toward your nose from a distance": "",
  "Pour the chemical onto a tissue and hold the tissue up to your nose": "",
  "Ask another student to smell it first and then describe it to you": "",
  "The wafting technique is the safe way to detect a chemical's odor. Hold the container away from your face and use your hand to gently fan a small amount of vapor toward your nose.": "",
  "What is a Material Safety Data Sheet (MSDS/SDS)?": "",
  "A document that provides detailed safety information about a chemical substance": "",
  "A sheet used to record experimental data during a laboratory experiment": "",
  "A form that students sign to confirm they completed the laboratory work": "",
  "A list of all the equipment available for use in a science laboratory": "",
  "A Material Safety Data Sheet (MSDS), now called a Safety Data Sheet (SDS), provides information about a chemical's hazards, handling procedures, first aid measures, and proper disposal methods.": "",
  "What is the 'wafting technique'?": "",
  "A safe method for detecting odors by fanning vapors toward your nose gently": "",
  "A technique for heating chemicals evenly over an open flame in the lab": "",
  "A method for pouring chemicals from one container to another without spilling": "",
  "A method for cleaning up chemical spills on the laboratory bench surface": "",
  "Wafting is a safe method for smelling chemicals. You hold the container about 6 inches from your face and use your hand to gently wave the air above the container toward your nose, avoiding direct inhalation.": "",
  "What does 'PPE' mean in laboratory safety?": "",
  "Personal Protective Equipment, such as goggles, gloves, and lab coats": "",
  "Properly Prepared Experiments, meaning procedures that are ready to go": "",
  "Pre-Planned Evaluation, referring to the test given after every lab class": "",
  "Physical Properties of Elements, a term used in chemistry classification": "",
  "PPE stands for Personal Protective Equipment. It includes items like safety goggles, gloves, lab coats, and closed-toe shoes that protect the body from chemical, physical, and biological hazards.": "",
  "What is a 'hazard' in a laboratory?": "",
  "Anything that has the potential to cause harm, injury, or damage": "",
  "A piece of equipment that is used to measure temperature values": "",
  "A type of chemical reaction that produces light and heat energy": "",
  "A lab activity that requires more than one student to complete": "",
  "A hazard is any source of potential harm or danger. In a lab, hazards include chemicals, open flames, sharp objects, electrical equipment, and biological materials.": "",
  "What is an 'eyewash station'?": "",
  "A safety device that provides a steady stream of water to flush eyes": "",
  "A special sink used only for washing laboratory glassware equipment": "",
  "A magnifying lens used to examine small objects during experiments": "",
  "A cabinet where extra pairs of safety goggles are stored for use": "",
  "An eyewash station is a safety device that delivers a gentle stream of water to rinse chemicals or debris from the eyes. It should be used for at least 15 minutes if a chemical splash occurs.": "",
  "What does 'flammable' mean?": "",
  "Capable of catching fire and burning easily when exposed to a flame or spark": "",
  "A substance that dissolves easily in water and forms a clear solution": "",
  "A material that is extremely cold and must be handled with thick gloves": "",
  "A chemical that changes color when it is mixed with another substance": "",
  "Flammable means a substance can easily catch fire and burn. Flammable materials like alcohol and certain gases must be kept away from open flames and heat sources in the laboratory.": "",
  "What does 'corrosive' mean on a chemical label?": "",
  "The chemical can destroy or damage skin, eyes, and other materials on contact": "",
  "The chemical is safe to handle without any protective equipment at all": "",
  "The chemical will evaporate quickly when exposed to room temperature air": "",
  "The chemical is a solid that can be safely stored at room temperature": "",
  "Corrosive means the chemical can destroy living tissue (skin, eyes) and damage materials like metals. Strong acids and bases are common corrosive substances that require gloves and goggles.": "",
  "What is a 'fire blanket' used for in a lab?": "",
  "Wrapping around a person whose clothing has caught fire to smother flames": "",
  "Covering lab equipment overnight to protect it from dust accumulation": "",
  "Insulating hot beakers to prevent them from cooling down too rapidly": "",
  "Wiping down lab benches after an experiment to clean the surface area": "",
  "A fire blanket is a sheet of fire-resistant material used to smother small fires or wrap around a person whose clothing is on fire. It works by cutting off the oxygen supply to the flames.": "",
  "What does 'toxic' mean on a chemical warning label?": "",
  "The substance is poisonous and can cause illness or death if ingested or inhaled": "",
  "The substance is extremely cold and should be stored in a warm location": "",
  "The substance has a very strong odor that is unpleasant but not harmful": "",
  "The substance is biodegradable and safe to pour directly down any drain": "",
  "Toxic means a substance is poisonous. Exposure through ingestion, inhalation, or skin contact can cause serious illness or death. Toxic chemicals require extra precautions like fume hoods and protective gloves.": "",
  "What is a 'safety shower' in a laboratory?": "",
  "A shower that quickly drenches a person to wash off chemicals from their body": "",
  "A regular bathroom shower located near the laboratory for personal hygiene": "",
  "A spray bottle used to rinse laboratory glassware between experiment steps": "",
  "A device that sprays disinfectant throughout the lab at the end of class": "",
  "A safety shower delivers a large volume of water to quickly rinse chemicals off a person's body or clothing. It is used in emergencies when a large chemical spill contacts the skin or clothing.": "",
  "A student is heating a test tube and points the opening toward her lab partner. What safety rule is she violating?": "",
  "She should heat the test tube from the bottom, not from the side": "",
  "She should point the test tube opening away from all people nearby": "",
  "She should never heat a test tube under any circumstances in lab": "",
  "She should hold the test tube with her bare hands while heating it": "",
  "When heating a test tube, always point the opening away from yourself and others. Hot liquids can suddenly boil and shoot out (bumping), which could burn someone if the tube is pointed at them.": "",
  "During a chemistry lab, a student spills acid on her hand. What should she do first?": "",
  "Wipe it off with a paper towel and continue working on the lab": "",
  "Rinse the area immediately with large amounts of running water": "",
  "Apply a bandage over the area without rinsing it off first": "",
  "Wait until the end of class to wash the area with soap only": "",
  "Immediately rinse the affected area under running water for at least 15–20 minutes. Then notify the teacher. Quick rinsing dilutes the acid and minimizes chemical burns.": "",
  "A student notices a cracked beaker on the shelf. What should she do?": "",
  "Use it anyway since it only has a small crack in the glass": "",
  "Report it to the teacher and do not use it because it could break and cause injury": "",
  "Tape over the crack with masking tape and use it carefully for the experiment": "",
  "Put it back on the shelf and let someone else deal with the cracked glass": "",
  "Cracked glassware should never be used because it can shatter when heated or stressed, causing cuts and spills. Report it to the teacher so it can be properly disposed of and replaced.": "",
  "A fire starts on a lab bench from an alcohol lamp. It is small and contained to a paper towel. What is the best immediate action?": "",
  "Blow on the fire to try to put it out with your breath quickly": "",
  "Pour water from the sink directly onto the burning alcohol lamp": "",
  "Alert the teacher and use a fire extinguisher or fire blanket to smother it": "",
  "Ignore it because small fires always burn themselves out in seconds": "",
  "Alert the teacher immediately. A fire blanket or fire extinguisher can smother a small fire. Never use water on an alcohol fire, as it can spread the burning liquid. Never try to blow out a chemical fire.": "",
  "A student is working with a Bunsen burner and her loose sleeve catches fire. What should she do?": "",
  "Run out of the room as fast as possible to get away from the flame": "",
  "Stop, drop to the ground, and roll to smother the flames on her clothing": "",
  "Wave her arms rapidly to fan the flames and blow them out with the air": "",
  "Try to pull the burning clothing off as quickly as she possibly can": "",
  "Stop, drop, and roll is the correct response when clothing catches fire. Running feeds oxygen to the flames and makes them worse. A fire blanket or safety shower can also be used.": "",
  "A student finishes an experiment and has leftover chemicals. Where should she dispose of them?": "",
  "Pour them all down the sink drain with plenty of running water": "",
  "In the designated chemical waste container as instructed by the teacher": "",
  "Put them back in the original chemical bottle with the other chemicals": "",
  "Throw them in the regular classroom trash can with other garbage": "",
  "Leftover chemicals must go in designated waste containers. Pouring chemicals down the drain can damage pipes and harm the environment. Putting them back in the original bottle can contaminate the stock chemical.": "",
  "A student wants to check if a clear liquid is water by tasting it. Why is this extremely dangerous?": "",
  "Because the liquid might have an unpleasant flavor that ruins his appetite": "",
  "Because many dangerous chemicals are clear and odorless but can cause harm": "",
  "Because the teacher might see him and deduct points from his final grade": "",
  "Because tasting liquids changes their chemical composition and ruins the lab": "",
  "Never taste anything in the lab. Many hazardous chemicals (acids, bases, poisons) look just like water. Tasting unknown substances can cause chemical burns, poisoning, or even death.": "",
  "A student is carrying a microscope across the room. What is the safest way to carry it?": "",
  "Hold it by the eyepiece with one hand while walking quickly": "",
  "Carry it with one hand on the arm and one hand under the base": "",
  "Slide it across the lab bench to the new location without lifting": "",
  "Hold it by the power cord and let it swing freely while walking": "",
  "Always carry a microscope with two hands — one on the arm and one supporting the base. This prevents dropping the expensive and fragile equipment. Walk slowly and carefully.": "",
  "A student smells a strong chemical odor coming from a bottle that was left open. She starts to feel dizzy. What should she do?": "",
  "Move away from the area to fresh air and immediately notify the teacher": "",
  "Continue working because dizziness is a normal part of doing lab work": "",
  "Cap the bottle herself and take deep breaths to clear her head faster": "",
  "Drink water to flush the chemical fumes out of her body immediately": "",
  "If you feel dizzy from chemical fumes, immediately move to fresh air and notify the teacher. Dizziness is a sign of toxic exposure. The teacher will ventilate the area and ensure everyone's safety.": "",
  "Before starting a lab, a student notices there is no safety equipment at her station. Her goggles are missing and the fire extinguisher area is blocked. What should she do?": "",
  "Start the lab without goggles since they are uncomfortable to wear anyway": "",
  "Report the missing equipment to the teacher and do not begin until it is resolved": "",
  "Borrow goggles from a student in another class who is not currently using them": "",
  "Begin the lab carefully and check for safety equipment during a break period": "",
  "Never begin a lab without proper safety equipment. Report missing goggles and blocked safety equipment to the teacher immediately. All safety equipment must be available and accessible before any work begins.": ""
}